# Apache reverse-proxy snippet for my-koto.
#
# Drop this inside an existing TLS <VirtualHost *:443> (the same one that
# already proxies other services). my-koto runs the standalone Next.js server
# on plain HTTP at localhost:3000 with basePath /my-koto.
#
# Enable the modules once:  a2enmod proxy proxy_http headers
#
# IMPORTANT — do NOT add security headers here. my-koto emits its own CSP
# (with a per-request nonce from middleware.ts), HSTS, Referrer-Policy,
# Permissions-Policy, COOP/CORP, and X-Content-Type-Options. Duplicating or
# overriding them in Apache breaks the nonce-based CSP. Let the app own them.

# Preserve the external Host so the app builds correct absolute URLs.
ProxyPreserveHost On

# my-koto. NOTE: no trailing slashes. Next.js uses trailingSlash=false, so the
# canonical path is /my-koto (without a slash) and /my-koto/ gets a 308 back to
# it. A slash-terminated ProxyPass (/my-koto/) would only match /my-koto/ and
# bounce in a redirect loop. The slash-less prefix matches /my-koto AND its
# /my-koto/_next/... assets.
ProxyPass        /my-koto http://localhost:3000/my-koto
ProxyPassReverse /my-koto http://localhost:3000/my-koto

# Notes:
# - The Next.js standalone server already serves /my-koto/_next/* static assets
#   and the PWA service worker at /my-koto/sw.js, so no Alias/DocumentRoot is
#   needed — everything goes through the proxy.
# - If you terminate HTTP/2, Next streaming still works over proxy_http/1.1;
#   no extra config required for this app.
# - Tailscale Funnel is NOT needed when Apache fronts the app; pick one.
